            "text": "is derived from ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "gâbia",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "’, “a cup” or “basin.”",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "For glory and for beauty.—It is certainly remarkable that so plain a dress as that of the ordinary priests—a white tunic, a girdle, which may or may not have been embroidered, and a plain white close-fitting cap—should be regarded as sufficing “for glory and for beauty.” White robes, however, are in Scripture constantly represented as eminently glorious (Daniel 7:9; Mark 9:3; John 20:12; Acts 1:10; Revelation 4:4; Revelation 6:11; Revelation 7:9-14; Revelation 15:6, &c.).",
        "children": [
          {
