  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verses 40-43.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - THE APPAREL OF THE ORDINARY PRIESTS. The chapter concludes with brief directions concerning the official attire of the ordinary priests. This was to consist of linen drawers like those of the high priest; of a tunic, also of linen (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 39:27",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), shaped like his, but not diapered; of a linen girdle, the exact character of which is not stated; and of a close-fitting cap. The entire dress, with perhaps the exception of the girdle, was white. The linen drawers were regarded as of primary necessity, and the priest who did not wear them was threatened with death. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 40.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "For Aaron's sons",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". His actual sons at this time - his descendants afterwards, to whom the priesthood was rigidly confined. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Thou shalt make coats",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The verb is different from that used in ver 39, and seems to imply that the priests' tunics were not to be patterned. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Girdles",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". It has generally been supposed that these were of the same material and workmanship as the high priest's; but this is nowhere stated. In ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 39:29",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", the high priest's girdle alone is spoken cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Bonnets",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Certainly not \"bonnets \"in the modern sense. Plain, close-fitting caps, shaped like a cup, or rather basin, seem to be meant. Such caps were often worn in Egypt, but not by the priests. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "For glory and for beauty",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". See above, ver. 2. It is very noticeable, that the extremely simple attire of the ordinary priests - a dress of pure white, without anything ornamental about it, unless it were the girdle - is still regarded as sufficient \"for glory and for beauty.\" White robes have certainly a vast amount of scriptural testimony in their favour (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 16:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Mark 9:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 20:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 1:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Revelation 4:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Revelation 6:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Revelation 7:9, 14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", etc.). Exodus 28:40",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The official dress of the sons of Aaron, i.e., of the ordinary priests, was to consist of just the same articles as Aaron's priestly costume (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 28:39",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). But their body-coat is called weavers' work in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 39:27",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and was therefore quite a plain cloth, of white byssus or cotton yarn, though it was whole throughout, ἀῤῥαφος without seam, like the robe of Christ (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 19:23",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). It was worn close to the body, and, according to Jewish tradition, reached down to the ankles (cf. Josephus, iii. 7, 2). The head-dress of an ordinary priest is called מגבּעה, related to גּביע a basin or cup, and therefore seems to have been in the form of an inverted cup, and to have been a plain white cotton cap. The girdle, according to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 39:29",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", was of the same material and work for Aaron and his sons. This dress was to be for glory and for beauty to the priests, just as Aaron's dress was to him (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 28:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). The glory consisted in the brilliant white colour, the symbol of holiness; whilst the girdle, which an oriental man puts on when preparing for the duties of an office, contained in the four colours of the sanctuary the indication that they were the officers of Jehovah in His earthly kingdom.",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]